In Java, delegation is a design pattern that allows an object to pass on its behavior (methods) to another object without directly implementing the methods in the subclass or even knowing about them at all. This can be achieved by using interfaces and abstract classes as delegate patterns are often used for this purpose. 

Here's how you could implement it:
```java
interface DaysToShipCalculator { int getDaysToShip(); }

abstract class Order implements DaysToShipCalculator{   // Abstract Class to hold common methods and properties of an order, like warehouse or priority plan. 
    protected Warehouse _warehouse;                     // Common property for all orders (like a reference).
}
class PriorityOrder extends Order {                      // SubClass with specific behavior related only to the 'PriorityPlan' object in addition/instead common properties and methods of an order, like priority plan. 
    protected PriorityPlan _priorityPlan;                // Specific property for this class (like a reference).  

    @Override                                           // Overriding method from abstract Order Class to provide specific behavior related only with 'Priority Plan' object and not common properties or methods of an order. 
    public int getDaysToShip() {                         // Specific implementation for the delegate pattern in PriorityOrder class, delegating responsibility towards _priorityPlan instead of warehouse/order details etc..  
        return this._priorityPlan.getDaysToShip();       // Delegation to specific behavior related with priority plan object and not common properties or methods like order's days-to-ship calculation from WareHouse class, which is handled by Order abstract Class in the beginning of code snippet above..
    } 
}  
```    
In this way you can use delegation to delegate specific behavior related with priority plan object and not common properties or methods like order's days-to-ship calculation from warehouse class, which is handled by Order abstract Class in the beginning of code snippet above. This design pattern allows for more flexible designs where different subclasses (like PriorityOrder) can have specific implementations based on their own requirements and delegation to other objects or classes as needed without modifying these base methods/properties directly, thus maintaining a clean separation between concerns in the system architecture.

